        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ‘statutes and judgments’. ‘Statutes’ are the appointed rules or regulations of conduct or ceremony, ‘judgments’ are the duties and rights determined by equity, authority, or custom. The phrase is however used very generally without any close distinction in the shades of meaning.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 10.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For Ezra had prepared his heart,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " etc. God's favour towards Ezra, and the prosperous issue of his journey, were the consequences of his having set his heart on learning God's will, and doing it, and teaching it to others. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To seek the law",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is to aim at obtaining a complete knowledge of it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To teach statutes and judgments",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is to inculcate both the ceremonial and the moral precepts. Ezra appears as a teacher of righteousness in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 10:10, 11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and again in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 8:2-18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " CHAPTER 7:11-28 THE DECREE OF ARTAXERXES WITH RESPECT TO EZRA (vers. 11-26). The present decree was of the nature of a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "firman",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " granted to an individual. It embodied, in the first place, a certain number of provisions which were temporary. Of this character were - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "1.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the permission accorded to all Persian subjects of Israelite descent to accompany Ezra to Jerusalem (ver. 13); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the commission to Ezra to convey to Jerusalem certain offerings made by the king and his chief courtiers to the God of Israel (vers. 15, 19); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the permission given him to convey to Jerusalem the free-will offerings of Jews and others resident in Babylonia (ver. 16); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "4.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " permission to Ezra to draw on the royal treasury to the amount of a hundred talents of silver, a hundred measures of wheat, a hundred \"baths\" of wine, a hundred \"baths\" of oil, and salt to any amount (ver. 22); and, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "5.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " an indefinite commission to \"inquire\" (ver. 14). Besides these temporary enactments, the decree contained certain provisions of a more permanent nature. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "1.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Ezra was invested with the chief authority over the whole district \"beyond the river,\" and was commissioned to appoint all the subordinate \"magistrates and judges\" (ver. 25). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " He was authorised to enforce his decisions by the penalties of imprisonment, confiscation of goods, banishment, and even death itself (ver. 26). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "Text_Heading",
        "text": "3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " An exemption from taxation of every kind was granted to all grades of the sacerdotal order - to the priests, the Levites, the singers, the porters, the Nethinim, and the lowest grade of \"ministers\" - to all, in fact, who were engaged in the performance of any sacred function connected with the temple (ver. 24). This last provision was absolutely permanent, and probably continued in force down to the close of the empire. Ezra 7:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "With Ezra went up a number of Israelites, priests, and Levites. מן partitive: a part of the whole. That they went up with Ezra appears from the context, and is expressly stated both in the royal edict (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and in the further description of the expedition (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 8:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). They went up in the seventh year of Artaxerxes, and reached Jerusalem in the fifth month of that year. - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Ezra is again, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the subject of the sentence; the intervening seventh verse being really only in apposition with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the time occupied by the journey is more precisely defined; כּי is explanatory. Namely, on the first day of the first month, he had appointed the journey from Babylon, etc. The Keri יסד הוּא can only mean, ipsum erat fundamentum profectionis, as J. H. Mich. after R. Sal. explains it, for יסד is pointed as the construct state. The departure of the expedition from the place of meeting occurred, according to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 8:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", on the twelfth day of the first month. Since, however, they encamped three days there, making the final preparations for their journey, eleven days might easily elapse between the period when the whole caravan had assembled, and the day of actual departure. The Keri offers no appropriate signification; for since הוּא can only be taken for the subject, and הם יסד for the predicate, the sentence would contain an anacoluthon. To translate הוּא by ipsum cannot be justified by the usages of the language, for there is no such emphasis on יסד as to cause הוּא to be regarded as an emphatic reference to the following noun. יסד must be pointed יסד or יסּד, as the third pers. perf. Kal or Piel, meaning to arrange, to appoint, and הוּא referred to Ezra. On הטּובה אלהיו כּיד, comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 7:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The hand of his God graciously arranged for him, for he had prepared his heart to seek and to do the law of Jahve, i.e., to make the law of God his rule of action. לבבו הכין, like ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 12:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 19:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 30:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". To teach in Israel statutes and judgments, as both are prescribed in the law of God. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]